---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import FaqSection from '../../components/FaqSection.astro';
import AdUnit from '../../components/AdUnit.astro';

const faq = [
  {
    question: "What is the difference between a JWT decoder and a Base64 decoder?",
    answer: "A Base64 decoder converts any Base64-encoded string back to its original text or binary data. A JWT decoder is specifically designed for JSON Web Tokens — it splits the token into its three parts (header, payload, signature), Base64url-decodes each part, and displays the JSON inside each section with proper formatting. Under the hood, JWT decoding uses Base64url decoding, but a JWT decoder adds token-specific structure, expiry checking, and claim visualization on top."
  },
  {
    question: "Can I decode a JWT with a regular Base64 decoder?",
    answer: "Partially. A JWT is made of three Base64url-encoded segments separated by dots. You can manually split the token on dots and Base64url-decode each part to read the header and payload. However, a standard Base64 decoder may not handle the URL-safe variant (- instead of +, _ instead of /). A dedicated JWT decoder handles all of this automatically and also formats the JSON claims for easy reading."
  },
  {
    question: "Is decoding a JWT the same as verifying it?",
    answer: "No. Decoding a JWT reads the claims inside the payload — it does not check the signature. Any tool can decode a JWT because the payload is only Base64url-encoded, not encrypted. Verification checks that the signature is valid using the secret or public key. Never trust the claims in a JWT just because you can read them — always verify the signature server-side before acting on the claims."
  },
  {
    question: "Is it safe to paste a JWT into an online decoder?",
    answer: "It depends on the token. If the JWT is a long-lived access token or contains sensitive claims, avoid pasting it into any third-party online tool, as it could be logged or exposed. For debugging purposes, use a self-hosted decoder or rotate the token after debugging. DevPlaybook's JWT builder runs entirely in your browser with no server requests, which minimizes the risk."
  },
  {
    question: "What is Base64url encoding and how does it differ from standard Base64?",
    answer: "Base64url is a variant of Base64 designed to be safe inside URLs and filenames. It replaces + with - and / with _, and omits the = padding characters. JWTs use Base64url for all three segments. Standard Base64 uses + and /, which have special meanings in URLs and must be percent-encoded. If you decode a JWT with a standard Base64 tool, you may need to manually swap these characters first."
  },
];
---

<BaseLayout
  title="JWT vs Base64 Decoder: Which to Use? (2025)"
  description="JWT decoder vs Base64 decoder — learn the difference, when each is the right tool, and why decoding a JWT is not the same as verifying it. Free JWT tool at DevPlaybook."
  faq={faq}
>
  <div class="max-w-3xl">
    <nav class="text-sm text-text-muted mb-4">
      <a href="/" class="hover:text-accent">Home</a>
      <span class="mx-2">/</span>
      <a href="/tools" class="hover:text-accent">Tools</a>
      <span class="mx-2">/</span>
      <span>JWT vs Base64 Decoder</span>
    </nav>

    <h1 class="text-3xl font-bold mb-3">JWT vs Base64 Decoder: Which to Use? (2025)</h1>
    <p class="text-text-muted mb-8 text-lg">JWTs use Base64url internally, but a dedicated JWT decoder gives you far more than raw decoding. Here's when each tool is the right choice.</p>

    <div class="bg-accent/10 border border-accent/20 rounded-lg p-5 mb-8">
      <p class="font-semibold text-white mb-1">Quick Answer</p>
      <p class="text-text-muted text-sm">Use a <strong class="text-white">JWT decoder</strong> for any JSON Web Token — it splits header/payload/signature and formats the claims. Use a <strong class="text-white">Base64 decoder</strong> for any other Base64-encoded data. Try <a href="/tools/jwt-builder" class="text-accent hover:underline">DevPlaybook's JWT Builder</a> to build, decode, and inspect tokens.</p>
    </div>

    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-4">Side-by-Side Comparison</h2>
    <div class="overflow-x-auto mb-8">
      <table class="w-full text-sm border-collapse">
        <thead>
          <tr class="bg-gray-800 text-white">
            <th class="text-left p-3 border border-gray-700">Feature</th>
            <th class="text-left p-3 border border-gray-700">JWT Decoder</th>
            <th class="text-left p-3 border border-gray-700">Base64 Decoder</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody class="text-text-muted">
          <tr>
            <td class="p-3 border border-gray-700 font-medium text-white">Input format</td>
            <td class="p-3 border border-gray-700">JWT (header.payload.sig)</td>
            <td class="p-3 border border-gray-700">Any Base64/Base64url string</td>
          </tr>
          <tr class="bg-gray-800/30">
            <td class="p-3 border border-gray-700 font-medium text-white">Splits token parts</td>
            <td class="p-3 border border-gray-700">Yes — header, payload, sig</td>
            <td class="p-3 border border-gray-700">No</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td class="p-3 border border-gray-700 font-medium text-white">Formats JSON claims</td>
            <td class="p-3 border border-gray-700">Yes</td>
            <td class="p-3 border border-gray-700">No</td>
          </tr>
          <tr class="bg-gray-800/30">
            <td class="p-3 border border-gray-700 font-medium text-white">Shows expiry (exp)</td>
            <td class="p-3 border border-gray-700">Yes — human-readable date</td>
            <td class="p-3 border border-gray-700">No</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td class="p-3 border border-gray-700 font-medium text-white">Verifies signature</td>
            <td class="p-3 border border-gray-700">Some tools (needs secret)</td>
            <td class="p-3 border border-gray-700">No</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>

    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-4">When to Use a JWT Decoder</h2>
    <ul class="list-disc list-inside text-text-muted mb-6 space-y-2 text-sm">
      <li>Inspecting the claims inside an access token or ID token during development</li>
      <li>Debugging authentication issues (wrong audience, expired token, missing claims)</li>
      <li>Understanding what a third-party JWT contains before trusting it</li>
      <li>Building or testing auth flows that issue JWTs</li>
    </ul>

    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-4">When to Use a Base64 Decoder</h2>
    <ul class="list-disc list-inside text-text-muted mb-6 space-y-2 text-sm">
      <li>Decoding a Base64-encoded string that is not a JWT</li>
      <li>Recovering text or binary data from a data URI</li>
      <li>Decoding Basic Auth credentials (<code class="text-accent">Authorization: Basic …</code>)</li>
      <li>Inspecting any Base64-encoded value in an API response or config file</li>
    </ul>

    <div class="bg-gray-800/50 border border-gray-700 rounded-lg p-6 mb-8 text-center">
      <p class="text-white font-semibold mb-2">Build and decode JWTs in your browser</p>
      <p class="text-text-muted text-sm mb-4">Free JWT builder and decoder — no sign-up, runs 100% in browser.</p>
      <a href="/tools/jwt-builder" class="inline-flex items-center gap-2 bg-accent hover:bg-accent/80 text-white font-medium px-5 py-2.5 rounded-lg transition-colors">
        Open JWT Builder →
      </a>
    </div>

    <AdUnit slot="auto" format="auto" label="Advertisement" />

    <FaqSection faq={faq} title="JWT vs Base64 Decoder — FAQ" />

    <div class="mt-8 text-sm text-text-muted">
      <p class="font-medium text-white mb-2">Related comparisons</p>
      <ul class="space-y-1">
        <li><a href="/compare/base64-vs-url-encoder" class="text-accent hover:underline">Base64 vs URL Encoder: Which to Use?</a></li>
        <li><a href="/compare/json-formatter-vs-validator" class="text-accent hover:underline">JSON Formatter vs Validator: Which to Use?</a></li>
        <li><a href="/compare/regex-tester-vs-generator" class="text-accent hover:underline">Regex Tester vs Generator: Which to Use?</a></li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </div>
</BaseLayout>
